
 1.
1. Load Data:
   - Open Tableau Desktop and connect to your GDP dataset.

2. Create a Symbol Map:
   - Drag Latitude to the Rows shelf.
   - Drag Longitude to the Columns shelf.
   - Assign geographic roles to Latitude and Longitude if necessary.

3. Add Country Names:
   - Drag Country Name to the Label shelf to display country names on the map.

4. Format the Map:
   - Adjust map styles, zoom levels, symbol sizes, and colors for readability.



 2. 
1. Create Bar Graph:
   - Drag Year to Columns shelf and GDP to Rows shelf.
   - Add a filter for Country and select Belgium.

2. Format the Graph:
   - Add title: *“GDP of Belgium (2006 – 2026)”*.
   - Adjust bar colors, axis labels, and gridlines for clarity.



 3. 
1. Create Pie Chart:
   - Drag Country Name to Rows shelf and GDP to Columns shelf.
   - Select Pie Chart from the Show Me panel.

2. Filter Data:
   - Filter Year for 2010 and select countries: India, Nepal, Romania, South Asia, Singapore.

3. Format Pie Chart:
   - Drag GDP to Label shelf for percentages.
   - Add title: *“GDP Distribution of Selected Countries (2010)”*.



 4. 
1. Create Chart:
   - Drag Country Name to Rows shelf and GDP to Columns shelf.
   - Filter Country Name for Bhutan and Costa Rica.

2. Format Chart:
   - Use bar or line chart.
   - Add title: *“GDP Comparison: Bhutan vs. Costa Rica”*.



 5. 
1. Create Scatter Plot:
   - Drag Year to Columns shelf and GDP to Rows shelf.
   - Filter for years (2004–2006) and countries (Mexico, Algeria, Fiji, Estonia).

2. Format Plot:
   - Add colors and sizes to differentiate countries.
   - Add title: *“GDP Comparison of Selected Countries (2004–2006)”*.
